#header:
  #-: Zerolang Type Representation

#nav id=toc class=toc-sidebar:
  #div id=tocfile: Table of Contents
  #doc.toc


This document specifies the memory representation and allocation strategy for
all types in Zerolang. It supersedes the heap-allocation model for user-defined
reftypes described in earlier versions and serves as the implementation plan for
the refactoring.


#-: Overview

#--: Design Principles

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Stack by default. Every user-defined type -- record, class, variant,
  union, protocol instance, facet instance -- lives on the stack. The struct
  that describes the object is a local variable or a field inside another
  struct. No #~"malloc" / #~"free" for the struct itself.]
  [#*: #+ Heap for data buffers only. The only heap allocations are
  #~"box" (a single object on the heap), #~"list" data buffers, #~"string"
  data buffers, and union subtype data. The controlling struct for #~"list"
  and #~"string" (length, capacity, pointer) still lives on the stack.]
  [#*: #+ Ownership tied to type class. Valtypes (records, variants) are
  freely copyable. Reftypes (classes, unions, protocol instances) are
  single-owner and cannot be copied -- only borrowed or taken.]
  [#*: #+ Flat valtypes. Valtypes may only contain other valtypes as fields.
  They cannot contain #~"string", #~"list", #~"box", or any other type that
  requires heap cleanup. This guarantees that valtypes are always trivially
  copyable and never need a destructor.]
  [#*: #+ Reftypes may own heap resources. Reftypes (classes, unions, protocol
  instances) may contain #~"string", #~"list", #~"box", or other reftype
  fields. However, a reftype is not required to own heap resources -- a class
  with only valtype fields is valid. Such a class still has identity and
  single-owner semantics but needs no destructor.]
  [#*: #+ Locks live on reftypes. The #~".lock" field mechanism is available to
  reftypes (classes) only. Valtypes (records, variants) cannot hold locks.
  Born-borrowed is removed as a concept.]


#--: Type Classification Summary

#table cols="3 2 2 2 2 2":
  Type                |Stack/Heap     |Copyable |Destructor          |Can have heap fields |.lock support
  record              |stack          |yes      |no                  |no                   |no
  variant             |stack          |yes      |no                  |no                   |no
  class               |stack          |no       |if heap fields      |yes                  |yes
  union               |stack (struct) |no       |yes (frees subdata) |yes (in subtypes)    |no
  protocol instance   |stack (struct) |no       |if wrapping reftype |yes (via wrapped)    |no
  facet instance      |stack          |yes      |no                  |no                   |no
  box(T)              |heap (data)    |no       |yes (free data)     |n/a                  |no
  list(T)             |stack (struct) |no       |yes (free data buf) |n/a                  |no
  string              |stack (struct) |no       |yes (free data buf) |n/a                  |no
  listview(T)         |stack          |no       |no                  |no                   |yes
  stringview          |stack          |no       |no                  |no                   |yes

Note: "enum" is not a separate type. Enums are variants or unions where every
subtype is #~"null" -- the struct collapses to just a tag discriminator.


#--: Method Receiver (#~"this")

For all type instances with methods, #~"this" is always passed as a pointer at
the C level. This applies to records, classes, unions, and any other type with
methods. The pointer convention ensures:

#ul:
  [#*: Methods can mutate fields and have those mutations persist across calls.]
  [#*: Method bodies work identically for stack-allocated and boxed instances --
  #~"box(T)" is already a pointer, so calling a method on a boxed value passes
  the pointer directly without #~"&".]

At call sites, the emitter generates #~"&var" to pass the address of a stack
variable to a method:

#code language=c: """
  /* zerolang: counter.increment c */
  z_counter_increment(&zv_c);
  """


#-: Type Specifications


#--: Records (Valtypes)

Records are product value types. They are stack-allocated, freely copyable, and
never need a destructor.

#---: Memory Layout

A record is a C struct with all fields inline:

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      int64_t x;
      int64_t y;
  } z_point_t;
  """

#---: Field Restrictions

Record fields must be valtypes: numeric types, bools, other records, variants,
function references. Records #_*"cannot" contain #~"string", #~"list",
#~"box", #~"map", classes, unions, or any type that requires heap cleanup.
This restriction is enforced by the type checker.

Records cannot have #~".lock" fields. Locks require identity (single-owner
semantics) which valtypes do not have. See the Born-Borrowed Analysis section
for discussion.

#---: Construction

#~"meta.create" returns the struct by value:

#code language=c: """
  static z_point_t z_point_meta_create(int64_t x, int64_t y) {
      z_point_t _this = {0};
      _this.x = x;
      _this.y = y;
      return _this;
  }
  """

#---: Ownership

Records are freely copied on assignment and passed by value to functions. Each
copy is independent. When a record falls out of scope it is simply forgotten --
no destructor runs.


#--: Variants (Valtypes)

Variants are sum value types (tagged unions). They are stack-allocated with
inline subtype data, freely copyable, and never need a destructor.

#---: Memory Layout

A variant uses an inline C union sized to the largest subtype:

#code language=c: """
  typedef enum {
      Z_SHAPE_TAG_CIRCLE,
      Z_SHAPE_TAG_RECT,
  } z_shape_tag_t;

  typedef struct {
      z_shape_tag_t tag;
      union {
          double circle;            /* radius */
          z_rect_t rect;            /* inline record */
      } data;
  } z_shape_t;
  """

The struct size is #~"sizeof(tag) + sizeof(largest subtype)". For enum-pattern
variants (all subtypes are #~"null"), the union is omitted entirely and the
struct is just #~"{ tag }".

#---: Field Restrictions

Variant subtypes must be valtypes. They cannot contain #~"string", #~"list",
#~"box", classes, unions, or any type requiring heap cleanup. This ensures
variants are trivially copyable and need no destructor.

#---: Ownership

Variants are freely copied (struct copy captures tag + active data). No
destructor is needed. When a variant falls out of scope, it is forgotten.


#--: Classes (Reftypes) -- Changed

Classes are product reference types. They are now #+ stack-allocated (changed
from heap-allocated). They have single-owner semantics: they cannot be copied,
only borrowed or taken.

#---: Memory Layout

A class is a C struct with all fields inline, stored on the stack:

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      z_string_t label;    /* string struct (stack), data buffer (heap) */
      int64_t value;
  } z_named_t;
  """

There is no #~"malloc" for the struct itself. The struct lives in the stack
frame of the declaring scope.

#---: Field Types

Classes may contain any field type: valtypes, other reftypes, #~"string",
#~"list", #~"box", and #~"map". A class is not required to have heap-backed
fields -- a class with only valtype fields is valid. Such a class still has
identity and single-owner semantics (cannot be copied) but needs no destructor.

#---: Construction

#~"meta.create" returns the struct by value (not a pointer):

#code language=c: """
  static z_named_t z_named_meta_create(z_string_t label, int64_t value) {
      z_named_t _this = {0};
      _this.label = label;
      _this.value = value;
      return _this;
  }
  """

At the call site, the class variable is a stack local:

#code language=c: """
  z_named_t n = z_named_create(z_string_new("test"), 42);
  """

#---: Destructor

A class destructor is emitted only if the class has fields that require
cleanup (string, list, box, map, or other reftypes with destructors). The
destructor cleans up those fields but does #_*"not" free the struct itself:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_named_destroy(z_named_t* p) {
      if (!p) return;
      z_string_free(&p->label);   /* free string data buffer */
      /* NO free(p) -- struct is on the stack */
  }
  """

If a class has no heap-backed fields (only valtypes), no destructor is emitted
and the variable is not added to the scope cleanup list.

#---: Ownership Transfer (.take)

Taking a class copies the struct (C struct assignment) and zero-initialises the
source. Zero-initialisation sets all pointer fields to #~"NULL", preventing
double-free when the source's scope cleanup runs:

#code language=c: """
  z_named_t d = zv_c;                         /* struct copy */
  zv_c = (z_named_t){0};                      /* invalidate source */
  """

#---: .release

#~".release" calls the destructor (if present) and zero-initialises the struct:

#code language=c: """
  z_named_destroy(&zv_n);
  zv_n = (z_named_t){0};
  """

#---: Scope Cleanup

When an owned class variable falls out of scope, the destructor is called (if
the type has one). The cleanup code passes #~"&var" to the destructor:

#code language=c: """
  z_named_destroy(&zv_n);
  """

#---: Function Returns

Functions returning a class return the struct by value. C compilers apply NRVO
(Named Return Value Optimisation) in practice, avoiding unnecessary copies.

#---: Parameter Passing

Borrow parameters receive a pointer (the caller passes #~"&var"). Take
parameters receive the struct by value (the caller copies the struct and
zero-initialises its source).

#---: Swap

Swapping two class variables swaps the entire struct:

#code language=c: """
  {
      z_named_t _tmp = zv_a;
      zv_a = zv_b;
      zv_b = _tmp;
  }
  """

#---: .lock Fields on Classes (New)

Classes may have #~".lock" fields. A class with #~".lock" fields:

#ul:
  [#*: Holds compile-time locks on the targets of its #~".lock" fields for the
  lifetime of the class instance.]
  [#*: Cannot be stored as a field of another type (prevents the lock from
  outliving its target).]
  [#*: Can be moved via #~".take" -- ownership and locks transfer to the new
  name.]
  [#*: Can be passed to #~".borrow" and #~".lock" parameters.]
  [#*: When the instance falls out of scope, locks are released (and the
  destructor runs if present).]

Classes with #~".lock" fields are normal owned instances. The single-owner
semantics of classes (no copying) already provide the safety guarantees that
born-borrowed previously enforced for records. A class cannot be duplicated, so
there is no risk of multiple copies holding the same lock.

#~".lock" fields are immutable after construction.


#--: Unions (Reftypes) -- Changed

Unions are sum reference types. They are now #+ stack-allocated (the struct
itself). The subtype data remains heap-allocated via a #~"void*" pointer.

#---: Memory Layout

A union is always two pointer-widths (16 bytes): a tag and a #~"void*":

#code language=c: """
  typedef enum {
      Z_RESULT_TAG_OK,
      Z_RESULT_TAG_ERR,
  } z_result_tag_t;

  typedef struct {
      z_result_tag_t tag;
      void* data;           /* heap-allocated subtype data */
  } z_result_t;
  """

The struct is 16 bytes on the stack regardless of subtype sizes. Subtype data
is heap-allocated and owned by the union.

#---: Subtype Data

Union subtypes may be reftypes or valtypes. The subtype data is always
heap-allocated:

#ul:
  [#*: For valtype subtypes: #~"malloc(sizeof(subtype))" + copy value.]
  [#*: For reftype subtypes (classes, strings, etc.): #~"malloc(sizeof(subtype))"
  + move (take) the struct into the heap allocation, invalidating the source.]
  [#*: For #~"null" subtypes: #~"data" is #~"NULL".]

Because union subtypes can be reftypes, a union may indirectly contain
#~"string", #~"list", #~"box", and other heap-backed fields within its
subtypes.

#---: Destructor

The destructor switches on the tag, cleans up the active subtype, frees the
subtype data, but does #_*"not" free the union struct:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_result_destroy(z_result_t* u) {
      if (!u) return;
      switch (u->tag) {
          case Z_RESULT_TAG_OK:
              break;
          case Z_RESULT_TAG_ERR:
              z_string_free((z_string_t*)u->data);
              free(u->data);
              break;
      }
  }
  """

A union always needs a destructor if any subtype has non-null data (to free the
heap allocation for the subtype data).

#---: Construction

Subtype construction allocates and stores the data:

#code language=c: """
  z_result_t r = {0};
  r.tag = Z_RESULT_TAG_OK;
  r.data = malloc(sizeof(int64_t));
  *(int64_t*)r.data = 42;
  """

For null subtypes:

#code language=c: """
  z_result_t r = {0};
  r.tag = Z_RESULT_TAG_ERR;
  r.data = NULL;
  """

#---: Match / Case

Match arms cast #~"data" to the subtype:

#code language=c: """
  switch (zv_r.tag) {
      case Z_RESULT_TAG_OK:
          printf("%lld\n", *(int64_t*)zv_r.data);
          break;
      case Z_RESULT_TAG_ERR:
          z_string_free((z_string_t*)zv_r.data);
          break;
  }
  """


#--: Protocol Instances -- Changed

Protocol instances are existential type wrappers. They are now
#+ stack-allocated (the wrapper struct). The wrapped data may be a borrowed
pointer or an owned heap copy.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      void (*method1)(void*, ...);
      void (*method2)(void*, ...);
      ...
  } z_printable_vtable_t;

  typedef struct {
      void* data;                       /* pointer to implementation */
      z_printable_vtable_t* vtable;     /* pointer to static vtable */
      void (*destroy)(void*);           /* destructor (NULL if borrowed) */
  } z_printable_t;
  """

The protocol struct (3 pointers = 24 bytes) is on the stack.

#---: Borrowed vs Owned

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Borrowed (#~"protocol.borrow"): #~"data" points to the source
  variable (via #~"&var"). #~"destroy" is #~"NULL". The protocol instance does
  not own the data.]
  [#*: #+ Owned (#~"protocol.create"): #~"data" points to a heap-allocated
  copy of the implementation. #~"destroy" is set to a cleanup function that
  frees the copy. For reftype implementations, the cleanup function calls the
  implementation's destructor before freeing.]

#---: Destructor

The protocol destructor calls #~"destroy" if set, then does #_*"not" free the
protocol struct (it is on the stack):

#code language=c: """
  static void z_printable_destroy(z_printable_t* p) {
      if (!p) return;
      if (p->destroy) p->destroy(p->data);
      /* NO free(p) -- struct is on the stack */
  }
  """

Since the wrapped data may be a reftype that contains #~"string", #~"list",
#~"box", etc., protocol instances may indirectly own heap resources.


#--: Facet Instances

Facet instances are value-type existential wrappers. They are stack-allocated
with inline data and are freely copyable.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef union {
      z_impl1_t _impl1;
      z_impl2_t _impl2;
  } z_iterable_data_u;

  typedef struct {
      z_iterable_vtable_t* vtable;      /* pointer to static vtable */
      z_iterable_data_u data;            /* inline data union */
  } z_iterable_t;
  """

The data is stored inline (not via pointer). The facet struct size is
#~"sizeof(vtable pointer) + sizeof(largest conforming type)".

#---: Restrictions

Because facets are valtypes, their implementations must be valtypes (records,
variants). They cannot wrap reftypes (classes, unions) and therefore cannot
indirectly contain #~"string", #~"list", #~"box", or other heap-backed fields.
No destructor is needed.


#--: box(T)

#~"box" is a generic type that heap-allocates a single instance of any type.
The C representation is a pointer to the inner type.

#---: Memory Layout

For #~"box(point)" where point is #~"{ i64 x, i64 y }":

#code language=c: """
  /* C type: z_point_t*  (pointer to heap-allocated point struct) */
  z_point_t* b = (z_point_t*)malloc(sizeof(z_point_t));
  *b = z_point_create(1, 2);
  """

#---: Transparency

Boxed items support all field and method access directly. The compiler handles
the indirection. There is no automatic unboxing: passing a boxed item to a
function requires the function to accept exactly that boxed type.

Since #~"this" is always a pointer in methods, all method bodies work on both
boxed (heap pointer) and unboxed (stack, via #~"&var") instances without
modification.

#---: Destructor

The box destructor frees the heap allocation. If the inner type has a
destructor (eg. a class with heap fields), that destructor is called first:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_box_named_destroy(z_named_t* v) {
      if (!v) return;
      z_named_destroy(v);    /* clean up inner type's heap fields */
      free(v);               /* free the box allocation */
  }
  """

For simple valtypes (no destructor), the box destructor is just #~"free(v)".

#---: Born-Boxed Construction

When a type is defined as a boxed type at the unit level, construction should
allocate directly on the heap and construct in-place. This avoids the overhead
of constructing on the stack then copying to the heap.

The box's #~"meta.create" does the heap allocation and field initialisation
in one step:

#code language=c: """
  static z_point_t* z_box_point_meta_create(int64_t x, int64_t y) {
      z_point_t* _this = (z_point_t*)malloc(sizeof(z_point_t));
      *_this = (z_point_t){0};
      _this->x = x;
      _this->y = y;
      return _this;
  }
  """

This is the heap-allocating version of #~"meta.create" -- the same pattern
currently used for classes, now repurposed for box types only.

#---: Boxing a Pre-Existing Item

When boxing a variable that already exists:

#code language=zerolang: """
  p: point x: 1 y: 2
  b: box from: p
  """

The compiler generates: allocate on heap, copy the value. If the source is a
reftype, #~".take" semantics apply -- the source is zero-initialised to prevent
double-free.

#---: Swap

Swapping two boxed items of the same type is a pointer swap:

#code language=c: """
  {
      z_point_t* _tmp = zv_a;
      zv_a = zv_b;
      zv_b = _tmp;
  }
  """

Swapping a boxed item with an unboxed item of the same underlying type is
#_*"not" supported. This would require a move-in/move-out dance that is
error-prone. The programmer should unbox/rebox explicitly if needed.


#--: list(T)

#~"list" is a generic growable array. The struct lives on the stack; only the
data buffer is heap-allocated.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      uint64_t length;
      int64_t* data;        /* heap-allocated data buffer */
      uint64_t capacity;
  } z_list_i64_t;
  """

Field order: #~"length" first, #~"data" second, #~"capacity" last. This order
is chosen so that the first two fields (#~"length", #~"data") match the
#~"listview" layout, enabling zero-cost casting from #~"list*" to
#~"listview*". Capacity is last because it is not present in views.

The struct (24 bytes) is on the stack. The #~"data" pointer references a
heap-allocated buffer sized to #~"capacity * sizeof(element)".

#---: Construction

#~"create" returns the struct by value (not a pointer):

#code language=c: """
  static z_list_i64_t z_list_i64_create(uint64_t _capacity) {
      z_list_i64_t _this = {0};
      _this.capacity = _capacity;
      if (_capacity > 0) {
          _this.data = (int64_t*)calloc(_capacity, sizeof(int64_t));
      }
      return _this;
  }
  """

#---: Destructor

The destructor frees the data buffer (and element destructors for reftype
elements). It does #_*"not" free the struct:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_list_i64_destroy(z_list_i64_t* p) {
      if (!p) return;
      free(p->data);
      /* NO free(p) -- struct is on the stack */
  }
  """

For reftype elements:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_list_string_destroy(z_list_string_t* p) {
      if (!p) return;
      for (uint64_t i = 0; i < p->length; i++) {
          z_string_free(&p->data[i]);
      }
      free(p->data);
  }
  """

#---: Growth Formula

Unchanged: #~"new_cap = cap + (cap >> 1) + 4" (approximately 1.5x + 4).

#---: Methods

All methods (append, insert, extend, get, set, pop, grow) take #~"this" as a
pointer. Call sites pass #~"&var".

#---: In-Place Element Creation

For creating elements directly in the data buffer (avoiding a stack temporary
+ copy), two approaches are possible:

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Append-then-init: append a zero-initialised element, then return a
  pointer to the last slot for the caller to initialise.]
  [#*: #+ Placement-style: provide a variant of append that takes construction
  arguments and constructs the element in-place.]

Recommendation: defer in-place creation to a future optimisation. The current
pattern (construct element on stack, append copies it into data buffer) is
correct and the copy cost is negligible for element-sized data.


#--: listview(T) (New)

#~"listview" is a generic read-only view into a list. It is a class (single
ownership) with a #~".lock" field that holds a lock on the parent list.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      uint64_t length;
      int64_t* data;        /* pointer into parent list's data buffer */
  } z_listview_i64_t;
  """

Field order matches the first two fields of #~"list": #~"length" first,
#~"data" second. This enables zero-cost casting from a #~"z_list_i64_t*" to a
#~"z_listview_i64_t*" -- the memory is reinterpreted without copying.

#---: Ownership

Listview is a class (reftype): single ownership, cannot be copied. It holds a
#~".lock" on the source list, preventing mutation of the list while the view
exists. When the listview falls out of scope, the lock is released.

Listview does #_*"not" need a destructor (no heap allocations of its own). The
data it points to is owned by the parent list.

#---: Locking

The listview holds a compile-time lock on the source list:

#code language=zerolang: """
  nums: (list of: i64)
  nums.append from: 10
  nums.append from: 20
  nums.append from: 30
  v: nums.toview             # v locks nums
  print v.get i: 0.u64       # OK: read through view
  # nums.append from: 40     # ERROR: nums is locked by v
  # when v falls out of scope, nums is unlocked
  """

#---: Methods

#ul:
  #*: #~"get(i: u64) out of" -- bounds-checked element access
  #*: #~"length() out u64" -- number of elements in the view
  #*: #~"list() out list" -- materialise a new owned list from the view (copies data)

#---: Zerolang Definition

#code language=zerolang: """
  listview: class {
      get: function {:this i: u64} out of is native
      length: function {:this} out u64 is native
      list: function {:this} out (list of: of) is native
  } as {
      of: any.generic
  }
  """


#--: string -- Changed

#~"string" is a growable UTF-8 byte buffer. The struct lives on the stack; only
the data buffer is heap-allocated. This is changed from the current
flexible-array-member design where the entire string (struct + data) was a
single heap allocation.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      uint64_t size;          /* byte count of current content */
      char* data;             /* heap-allocated data buffer */
      uint64_t capacity;      /* allocated buffer size */
  } z_string_t;
  """

Field order: #~"size" first, #~"data" second, #~"capacity" last. This matches
the field order of #~"list" (#~"length", #~"data", #~"capacity") for
consistency. The first two fields (#~"size", #~"data") match #~"stringview"
layout, enabling zero-cost casting. Putting #~"size" first also enables a
future small-string optimisation (SSO) where the high bit of #~"size" marks
inline storage and the remaining bytes of the struct store the string data
directly.

The struct (24 bytes) is on the stack. The #~"data" pointer references a
heap-allocated buffer. Strings are null-terminated (for C interop) but #~"size"
tracks the actual content length.

#---: Construction

#code language=c: """
  static z_string_t z_string_new(const char* s) {
      z_string_t str = {0};
      if (s) {
          str.size = strlen(s);
          str.capacity = str.size + 1;
          str.data = (char*)malloc(str.capacity);
          memcpy(str.data, s, str.capacity);  /* includes null terminator */
      }
      return str;
  }
  """

#---: Destructor

Frees the data buffer only:

#code language=c: """
  static void z_string_free(z_string_t* s) {
      if (s && s->data) free(s->data);
  }
  """

#---: Growth Formula

Unchanged: #~"new_cap = cap + (cap >> 1) + 16" (approximately 1.5x + 16).

#---: Runtime Functions (Changed Signatures)

All runtime functions are updated for the new layout:

#table cols="4 6":
  Function                |Signature change
  #~"z_string_new"        |Returns #~"z_string_t" (was #~"z_string_t*")
  #~"z_string_cat"        |Returns #~"z_string_t" (was #~"z_string_t*"); args are #~"z_string_t*"
  #~"z_string_from_i64"   |Returns #~"z_string_t" (was #~"z_string_t*")
  #~"z_string_from_f64"   |Returns #~"z_string_t" (was #~"z_string_t*")
  #~"z_string_free"       |Takes #~"z_string_t*"; frees #~"data" only (not struct)
  #~"z_string_eq"         |Takes two #~"z_string_t*" args
  #~"z_string_reserve"    |Takes #~"z_string_t*" (unchanged -- already pointer)
  #~"z_string_append"     |Takes #~"z_string_t*" (unchanged -- already pointer)
  #~"z_string_shrink"     |Takes #~"z_string_t*" (unchanged -- already pointer)
  #~"z_string_create"     |Returns #~"z_string_t" (was #~"z_string_t*")
  #~"z_string_print"      |Takes #~"z_string_t*"


#--: stringview -- Changed

#~"stringview" is now a #+ class (changed from born-borrowed record). It is a
read-only view into a #~"string", with single-owner semantics and a #~".lock"
on the source string.

#---: Memory Layout

#code language=c: """
  typedef struct {
      uint64_t length;        /* byte count of the viewed region */
      const char* data;       /* pointer into string's data buffer */
  } z_stringview_t;
  """

Field order: #~"length" first, #~"data" second. This matches the first two
fields of #~"string" (#~"size", #~"data"), enabling zero-cost casting from
#~"z_string_t*" to #~"z_stringview_t*".

#---: Ownership

Stringview is a class (reftype): single ownership, cannot be copied. It holds a
#~".lock" on the source string (when created from a string variable).
Stringviews created from string literals point into static #~".rodata" and do
not lock anything (static data has infinite lifetime).

Stringview has no destructor (no heap allocations).

#---: Methods

#ul:
  #*: #~"length() out u64" -- byte count
  #*: #~"string() out string" -- materialise a new owned string from the view
  #*: #~"==(rhs: stringview) out bool" -- content comparison
  #*: #~"!=(rhs: stringview) out bool" -- negated comparison


#--: option / optionval -- Impact

#~"option" is a union with subtypes #~"{ some: T, none: null }". Under the new
model, the #~"option" struct (#~"{ tag, void* }") moves to the stack but its
subtype data is still heap-allocated (standard union behaviour).

The nullable-pointer optimisation (#~"is_nullable_ptr") is preserved: for
pointer-typed payloads (box, protocol, etc.), #~"option" is represented as a
bare pointer with #~"NULL" sentinel, avoiding the tag + void* overhead entirely.


#-: Born-Borrowed Analysis

#--: Removal from Valtypes

Born-borrowed is removed as a language concept. The #~".lock" field mechanism
is now available only to reftypes (classes). Valtypes (records, variants)
cannot hold locks.

#---: Rationale

The original motivation for born-borrowed was to allow stack-allocated records
to hold locked references to heap-allocated classes. Since records are
valtypes (freely copyable), the born-borrowed flag was needed to prevent copies
-- each copy would appear to hold a separate lock on the same target. This made
born-borrowed records neither truly values (they could not be copied) nor truly
references (they had no identity or destructor).

With classes now stack-allocated, the motivation disappears. A class with
#~".lock" fields has single-owner semantics that naturally prevent copies,
without any special born-borrowed mechanism. The class can be moved
(#~".take"), which born-borrowed records could not do.

#---: Migration

Types that were born-borrowed records become classes:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"stringview": becomes a class with #~".lock" on the source string.]
  [#*: Iterators (eg. #~"bagiter"): become classes with #~".lock" on the
  container.]
  [#*: Any record with #~".lock" fields: becomes a class.]

#---: Critique

Removing born-borrowed from valtypes is a simplification but has trade-offs:

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Pro: Cleaner type system. Valtypes are always values -- freely
  copyable, no identity, no destructor, no locks. There is no hybrid category.]
  [#*: #+ Pro: More flexible. Class-based views and iterators support
  #~".take" (moving to a new name), which born-borrowed records could not do.]
  [#*: #+ Pro: Consistent locking. Locks live only on types with identity
  (reftypes). This is conceptually cleaner -- a lock pins a specific instance,
  which requires identity.]
  [#*: #+ Con: Performance. Born-borrowed records were passed by value (struct
  copy) for #~".take" parameters, which is efficient for small structs (eg.
  stringview = 16 bytes). Classes are passed by pointer for #~".borrow"
  parameters, adding one level of indirection. However, the struct sizes are
  identical and the indirection cost is negligible.]
  [#*: #+ Con: Existing code. All existing born-borrowed records must be
  migrated to classes. This is a one-time migration cost. The compiler should
  emit clear errors guiding the migration.]
  [#*: #+ Con: Semantic shift. A #~"stringview" that was previously a value
  (cheaply passed around, no ownership tracking) becomes a reference (needs
  ownership tracking, borrow annotations). This adds some friction for common
  string-passing patterns. However, since born-borrowed stringviews were
  already restricted (could not be copied or stored), the practical difference
  is small.]
  [#*: #+ Issue: String literals. String literals currently produce
  stringviews pointing into #~".rodata". If stringview is a class, string
  literals produce an owned class instance. Since #~".rodata" has static
  lifetime, there is no safety concern, but the ownership tracking adds
  overhead to a very common pattern. Consider: should string literals remain a
  special case that produces a freely-borrowable stringview without locking?
  This would require the compiler to recognise that #~".rodata"-backed
  stringviews need no lock.]


#-: Implementation History

The refactor was landed in ten phases, all of which are now #+ complete. Each
phase was independently testable and landed behind passing #~"make check &&
make test && make build". This section records the phase list for historical
reference; the type specifications earlier in this document describe the
current state.

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Phase 1 -- Destructor metadata. Split "struct needs free" from
  "struct has fields needing cleanup" in #~"ZType".]
  [#*: #+ Phase 2 -- Stack-allocate classes. Removed class heap allocation;
  class field access uses #~"." (only method #~"this" and boxed items use
  #~"->"); destructors emit only when a class has owned fields that need
  cleanup.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 3 -- Stack-allocate list structs. #~"list" struct on the
  stack; the data buffer remains on the heap.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 4 -- Rewrite string runtime. #~"z_string_t" becomes
  #~"{ size, data*, capacity }" on the stack with a heap data buffer.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 5 -- Stack-allocate unions. Union struct stays
  #~"{ tag, void* }" but lives on the stack; subtype data is heap-allocated.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 6 -- Stack-allocate protocol instances. Protocol wrapper is
  now a 24-byte stack struct; owned wrappers heap-allocate only a copy of
  the implementation.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 7 -- Extend #~".lock" fields to classes.]
  [#*: #+ Phase 8 -- Remove born-borrowed from valtypes. Records may no
  longer hold #~".lock" fields or heap-backed types; types that needed
  them became classes (#~"stringview", iterators, views).]
  [#*: #+ Phase 9 -- Implement #~"listview" as a read-only class view into
  a #~"list".]
  [#*: #+ Phase 10 -- Box refinements. #~"box(T)" adapted to work with
  stack-allocated classes and born-boxed construction.]

The compile-time restrictions that the refactor introduced are:

#ul:
  [#*: Record fields cannot be #~"string", #~"list", #~"box", #~"map" or any
  other heap-backed type. They also cannot be another user class or union.
  Records are pure valtypes.]
  [#*: #~".lock" fields are permitted on classes only. A record with a
  #~".lock" field is rejected.]
  [#*: A class (or any user-defined type) that has a #~".lock" field cannot
  appear as a field of another type.]

#--: Historical Phase Notes -- Scaffolding

The rest of this section is an internal record of the phase-by-phase
work items. It is retained for archaeology; none of the plans below are
outstanding.


#--: Phase 1: Foundation -- Destructor Metadata \[COMPLETE\]

Goal: separate "struct needs free" from "struct has fields needing cleanup" in
the type metadata.

