#-: Pros, Cons, and Risks


#--: Pros

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Simpler mental model. "Everything is on the stack. Only box and data
  buffers are on the heap." Easy to teach and reason about.]
  [#*: #+ Fewer allocations. Most programs see fewer #~"malloc"/#~"free" calls,
  improving performance and reducing fragmentation.]
  [#*: #+ Unified field access. Local variables of all types use #~"." for
  field access. Only #~"this" in methods and boxed items use #~"->".]
  [#*: #+ Class .lock fields. Enables natural class-based iterators and
  views. More flexible than the old born-borrowed record approach: a class
  instance supports #~".take" (moving to a new name).]
  [#*: #+ Clean type system. Valtypes are always values. Reftypes are always
  references with identity. No hybrid category.]
  [#*: #+ Predictable memory usage. Stack allocation makes memory usage more
  predictable and eliminates #~"malloc" failure risk for ordinary objects.]


#--: Cons

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Stack size. Large class structs consume stack space. For deeply
  recursive functions with large local classes, stack overflow is possible.
  Mitigation: #~"box(T)" provides explicit opt-in to heap allocation.]
  [#*: #+ Struct copy cost. Moving a large class (via #~".take" or function
  return) copies the entire struct. NRVO mitigates returns, but #~".take"
  always copies. For large structs, #~"box" should be preferred.]
  [#*: #+ Variant size. Inline tagged variants use the size of the largest
  subtype. For variants with subtypes of very different sizes, this wastes
  stack space. Rarely an issue in practice since variant subtypes must be
  valtypes (typically small).]
  [#*: #+ String rewrite risk. The string runtime rewrite (Phase 4) touches
  nearly every test.]
  [#*: #+ Born-borrowed migration cost. All born-borrowed records had to be
  rewritten as classes. One-time cost, now absorbed.]
  [#*: #+ Recursive types. Self-referential types (linked list nodes, tree
  nodes) must use #~"box(self)" for the recursive field. Error message should
  be clear.]


#--: Risks

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Test blast radius. ~1200 tests. Phases 2, 4, and 5 will each cause
  significant test breakage. Mitigation: phase incrementally.]
  [#*: #+ Protocol interaction. Protocol wrappers that own their data must
  heap-allocate a copy of the implementation. Verify this path works correctly
  after Phase 2.]
  [#*: #+ C ABI for large structs. Some platforms pass large structs via hidden
  pointer at the ABI level. Handled transparently by the C compiler.]
  [#*: #+ String literal stringviews. If stringview becomes a class, string
  literals produce owned class instances. Need to handle .rodata-backed
  stringviews specially (no lock needed).]


#-: Future Directions

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Small-string optimisation (SSO). The #~"size" field is first in the
  string struct. The high bit can mark inline storage. When set, the remaining
  bytes of the struct (data pointer + capacity = 16 bytes) store the string
  data directly, avoiding a heap allocation for strings up to 15 bytes. The
  same #~"size-first" layout applies to #~"stringview", #~"list", and
  #~"listview" for consistency.]
  [#*: #+ In-place list element creation. Construct elements directly in the
  data buffer without a stack intermediate.]
  [#*: #+ Box swap across types. Allow swapping #~"box(T)" with #~"T" for the
  same underlying type.]
  [#*: #+ Automatic boxing. Compiler-inferred boxing when a class is passed to
  a function expecting #~"box(T)".]
  [#*: #+ Move semantics. Elide struct copies when the compiler can prove the
  source is unused after the move.]
  [#*: #+ Arena allocation. Allow #~"box" and #~"list" to allocate from a
  user-provided arena.]


#-: Verification Plan

After each phase, run:

#ol:
  [#*: #~"make check" -- formatting, linting, type checking.]
  [#*: #~"make test" -- all pytest tests.]
  [#*: #~"make build" -- compile all examples to C and then to binaries.]
  [#*: Run compiled examples under ASan (#~"CFLAGS=-fsanitize=address make build")
  to detect memory errors, leaks, and undefined behaviour.]
  [#*: Manual inspection of generated C for one representative example per
  phase to verify the emitted code matches the specification.]
